pull_request.title: feat(order): 매수/매도/주문내역 API(MVP) + local(H2) 실행 설정
pull_request.body:
## 작업 내용 (MVP)
- 엔드포인트
  - POST /api/v1/orders/buy  (시장가 매수)
  - POST /api/v1/orders/sell (지정가/시장가 매도)
  - GET  /api/v1/orders      (주문 내역 페이지네이션)
- 도메인: Order, Repository, Service, Controller 구성
- 로컬 실행: local 프로필(H2)로 구동 확인
- 임시 브로커: FakeBrokerGateway (brokerOrderId = SIM-****)

## 로컬 실행
./gradlew bootRun --args='--spring.profiles.active=local'

### 확인 예시
- 매수(MARKET)
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/orders/buy \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"userId":1,"symbol":"005930","orderType":"MARKET","quantity":10}'
- 매도(LIMIT)
  curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/orders/sell \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"userId":1,"symbol":"005930","orderType":"LIMIT","quantity":5,"price":70000}'
- 주문 내역
  curl "http://localhost:8080/api/v1/orders?userId=1&page=0&size=20"

## 다음 단계
- 내일 KIS(AppKey/Secret, CANO, 상품코드) 수령 후 KisBrokerGateway로 실주문 연동
- Docker(Postgres) 전환
- demo 엔티티(H2 예약어 충돌) 정리

pull_request.body: ## 수정 사유 Reason for modification 소스를 수정한 사유가 무엇인지 체크해 주세요. Please check the reason you modified the source. ([X] X는 대문자여야 합니다.) - [ ] 버그수정 Bug fixes - [x] 기능개선 Enhancements - [ ] 기능추가 Adding features - [ ] 기타 Others ## 수정된 소스 내용 Modified source 검토자를 위해 수정된 소스 내용을 설명해 주세요. Please describe the modified source for reviewers. 사용자 요청에 따라 #0000FF와 흰색 조합의 모던하고 반응형 UI 테마를 적용하여 전반적인 디자인을 개선했습니다. 주요 변경 사항은 다음과 같습니다: * 새로운 `src/css/theme.css` 파일을 추가하여 전역 색상 변수 및 핵심 UI 컴포넌트(헤더, 버튼, 폼, 페이징, 채팅 등)에 테마를 적용했습니다. * `src/App.jsx`에 `theme.css`를 임포트하여 기존 스타일을 오버라이드했습니다. * `body`의 `min-width`를 해제하고 주요 레이아웃 컨테이너의 너비를 `min(1200px, 100%)`로 조정하여 반응형 레이아웃을 개선했습니다. * 주요 인터랙션 요소의 `:focus-visible` 아웃라인을 브랜드 색상으로 통일했습니다. ## JUnit 테스트 JUnit tests 테스트를 완료하셨으면 다음 항목에 [대문자X]로 표시해 주세요. docs: comprehensive workflow documentation and enterprise footer tracking (#53)

# 📚 Comprehensive Workflow Documentation & Enterprise Footer Tracking

## Enhanced Documentation Coverage

### 🧪 Smart Testing Strategy Documentation
- **Local vs CI Strategy**: Fast local tests (< 2 min) + comprehensive
CI tests leveraging unlimited GitHub Actions minutes
- **Cross-Platform Testing**: ARM64 (local) vs AMD64 (CI) compatibility
guidelines
- **Performance Testing**: Visual regression matrix (20 combinations),
accessibility audits, performance monitoring
- **Command Reference**: Complete testing command documentation with
timeouts and strategies

### 🔒 Security Scanning & Troubleshooting
- **TruffleHog Configuration**: Fixed BASE/HEAD commit issues for main
branch workflows
- **Context-Aware Scanning**: Differential (PR), single-commit (main),
full-repository (scheduled) modes
- **Security Troubleshooting**: Comprehensive guide for common GitHub
Actions security scanning issues
- **Vulnerability Management**: Complete workflow troubleshooting
reference

### 🏗️ CI/CD Pipeline Architecture Documentation
- **Three-Tier Deployment**: PR Preview → Netlify Staging → GitHub Pages
Production
- **Workflow Resilience**: Exponential backoff, circuit breaker
patterns, comprehensive error handling
- **Environment Management**: Clear separation and naming for AI and
human understanding
- **Version Management**: Release-please integration and semantic
versioning documentation

## Enterprise-Grade Footer Version Tracking

### 🌐 Cross-Environment Correlation System
- **Environment Detection**: Production, Staging, Preview, Development
with automatic URL-based detection
- **Build Metadata**: Version, commit SHA, build number, timestamps with
GitHub Actions integration
- **Repository Correlation**: Direct links to releases, commits, PRs,
and deployment workflows
- **Release Tracking**: Commits ahead counter, last release tag, compare
URLs for change tracking

### 📊 Version Display Features
- **Environment Badges**: Color-coded visual indicators (Production:
green, Staging: yellow, etc.)
- **Clickable Links**: All version elements link to relevant GitHub
resources
- **Context-Aware Display**: Different information based on deployment
environment
- **Mobile Responsive**: Professional display across all device types

### 🔗 Cross-Deployment Navigation
- **Release Notes**: Direct links to GitHub releases for production
versions
- **PR Context**: For preview deployments, shows PR number and branch
information
- **Staging Context**: Build metadata and deployment workflow links
- **Development Context**: Local development server and file
modification tracking

## Technical Implementation

### 📁 File Changes
- **CLAUDE.md**: 400+ lines of comprehensive documentation covering all
workflow aspects
- **template.html**: Enterprise footer with sophisticated environment
detection JavaScript
- **.claude/settings.local.json**: Enhanced configuration for better AI
assistant integration

### 🎯 User Experience Benefits
- **Instant Environment Identification**: Clear visual indicators of
which environment you're viewing
- **One-Click Navigation**: Jump between environments, releases, and
repository resources
- **Build Traceability**: Track any deployment back to its source commit
and workflow run
- **Release Correlation**: Understand exactly which version is deployed
where

### 🚀 Performance Impact
- **Zero Build Impact**: Footer JavaScript loads asynchronously without
blocking page rendering
- **Optimized Asset Loading**: Version information cached and loaded
efficiently
- **Mobile Performance**: Responsive design with minimal bandwidth usage
- **Cross-Browser Compatibility**: Works across all modern browsers and
devices

## Addresses User Requirements

✅ **Smart Testing Strategy**: "run long tests on CI and basically for
functionally local"
✅ **Unlimited GitHub Minutes**: "since this is a open repo github gives
us unlimited minutes"
✅ **AI Context**: "make sure everything its explicit and with context so
AI can always understand"
✅ **Enterprise Footer**: "on footer of site is easy to cross check this
with useful links"
✅ **Environment Tracking**: "instantaneous check what and the version
you are using at the time"
✅ **Documentation Upgrade**: Complete workflow documentation covering
all improvements

issue.title: bug: Quickgui wrongfully detects QEMU version
issue.body:
**I confirm this bug has not already been reported**
- [X] I have searched the issues and this bug has not been reported previously

**Describe the bug**
When installing quickgui from AUR or using the app image (Its not just the AUR package, both bin and git) the vm refuses to start because the version is wrongfully detected as outdated.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Download quickgui (AUR, AppImage)
2. run it from a terminal with "quickgui"
3. Go to Manage Existing Machines
4. Click start on a mac os vm
5. See the error in the terminal.

**Expected behavior**
Machine should start with QEMU and spicy be displayed

**Desktop (please complete the following information):**
 - Quickgui Versdion: 1.2.10
 - OS: Arch Linux - KDE Wayland
 - Version Rolling Release


**Additional context**
Logs:
[whoami@whoamilinux ~]$ quickgui
(Graphical Logs Redacted)
$ quickemu --vm macos-sonoma.conf --display spice
ERROR! QEMU 6.0.0 or newer is required, detected 10.0.3.
[ERROR:flutter/runtime/dart_vm_initializer.cc(41)] Unhandled Exception: ShellException(quickemu --vm macos-sonoma.conf --display spice, exitCode 1, workingDirectory: /home/whoami/quickemu-vms)

[whoami@whoamilinux ~]$

this is going to be tricky because it will run afoul of the auto-generated sequence docs.  We'll have to have a think about the "proper" way to do it.  Usually, the mechanism is to only wait for the things you want, not the other stuff.  WE can either have this initial bit 1) wait for a certain amount of _time_, or 2) wait for the condition it's actually looking for and then `checkThat` the time hasn't been too quick, with an internal check for an `UPDATING` state.

Too hard to write out in a comment here, so maybe I can/should do a quick hack on your PR to show you what I mean... or have a think.
